<line id="81"><marker></marker><content><span class="context-markup xml"><span class="text">      </span><span class="tag open"><span class="begin">&lt;body</span> <span class="attribute">mode=</span><span class="value">"formatted"</span><span class="end">&gt;</span></span><span class="tag open"><span class="begin">&lt;p</span><span class="end">&gt;</span></span><span class="text">Theology surfaced as a discipline from the rhetorical and philosophical traditions that were flourishing when Christianity started spreading around the Greco-Roman world from first-century Jewish Palestine. Therefore, theology as such is closely linked with the birth of Christianity as a world religion and its methods and questions cannot readily be applied to other belief systems such as Hinduism, Buddhism, Pantheism, etc. So theology was born as the response of the Christian faith to the questions that the Greeco-Roman world were asking at the time of their encounter.</span><span class="tag close">&lt;/p&gt;</span><span class="text"></span></span></content></line>
<line id="82"><marker></marker><content><span class="context-markup xml"><span class="text"></span></span></content></line>
<line id="83"><marker></marker><content><span class="context-markup xml"><span class="text"></span><span class="tag open"><span class="begin">&lt;h4</span><span class="end">&gt;</span></span><span class="text">A Historical Overview</span><span class="tag close">&lt;/h4&gt;</span><span class="text"></span></span></content></line>
<line id="84"><marker></marker><content><span class="context-markup xml"><span class="text"></span></span></content></line>
<line id="85"><marker></marker><content><span class="context-markup xml"><span class="text"></span><span class="tag open"><span class="begin">&lt;h5</span><span class="end">&gt;</span></span><span class="text">God is here</span><span class="tag close">&lt;/h5&gt;</span><span class="text"></span></span></content></line>
<line id="86"><marker></marker><content><span class="context-markup xml"><span class="text"></span></span></content></line>
<line id="87"><marker></marker><content><span class="context-markup xml"><span class="text"></span><span class="tag open"><span class="begin">&lt;p</span><span class="end">&gt;</span></span><span class="text">The concept emerged for the first time with the Greek philosopher Plato for whom theology referred to the mythical. Although he acknowledged some of its positive contributions to the life of the city and its inhabitants, Plato argued for a purge of those elements that he considered offensive and abstruse with the help of political legislation. In contrast to philosophers, "theologians" (e.g. the eighth-century-BCE Greek poets Hesiod and Homer, the cultic servants in the temple at Delphi, and the later rhetoricians who defended publicly the worship of the emperor) testified to the involvement of gods in human affairs. For example, Homer sets the outcome of the ten-year siege of Troy by a coalition of Greek states against the conflicting interests of different deities. Aphrodite rescues Paris when in danger whereas Hera out of hatred for the Trojans convinces Zeus to rekindle the war when it seemed to have reached a halt. Therefore, theology in its original Greek context offered an </span><span class="tag open"><span class="begin">&lt;em</span><span class="end">&gt;</span></span><span class="text">alternative</span><span class="tag close">&lt;/em&gt;</span><span class="text"> to historiography. The Christian faith, instead, presented itself not as an alternative but rather as an interpretation of history. The birth, life and death of Jesus which many could give testimony to were the very phenomenon through which God became part of His creation in order to redeem it. Unfortunately, the birth and death of our Saviour took a prominent place in the theological discussions of the time to the detriment of His life. The vision of the transformed community that seemed very much alive in the days following the Pentecost was soon lost.</span><span class="tag close">&lt;/p&gt;</span><span class="text"></span></span></content></line>
<line id="88"><marker></marker><content><span class="context-markup xml"><span class="text"></span></span></content></line>
<line id="89"><marker></marker><content><span class="context-markup xml"><span class="text"></span><span class="tag open"><span class="begin">&lt;h5</span><span class="end">&gt;</span></span><span class="text">Not the God they expected</span><span class="tag close">&lt;/h5&gt;</span><span class="text"></span></span></content></line>
<line id="90"><marker></marker><content><span class="context-markup xml"><span class="text"></span></span></content></line>
<line id="91"><marker></marker><content><span class="context-markup xml"><span class="text"></span><span class="tag open"><span class="begin">&lt;p</span><span class="end">&gt;</span></span><span class="text">Christian theologians accepted the agenda set forth by Greek mythology but besides having to argue God's involvement in history they've found themselves forced to explain the differences between the pagan deities and the Jewish Yahweh who had revealed Himself in the historical personality of Jesus. This was not an easy task at all especially because the Christian story did not seem to share anything with the stories about adulterous, arrogant and drunkard gods. Nor had there been anything heroic about Jesus, at least not according to the Greek ideals of heroism as described in the myth of Hercules. Faced with such a great challenge, early theologians emphasised God's nature as different from that of men which the Greek deities shared to a large extent. The God of Christians was eternal, incorruptible, unchangeable, omniscient, omnipresent, all powerful, and the ultimate standard for morality. Similarly Jesus' divinity became their main concern. While the reflections on God's nature raised the confidence of the young groups of believers around the Greco-Roman world they often failed to make sense of Jesus' humanity.</span><span class="tag close">&lt;/p&gt;</span><span class="text"></span></span></content></line>
<line id="92"><marker></marker><content><span class="context-markup xml"><span class="text"></span></span></content></line>
<line id="93"><marker></marker><content><span class="context-markup xml"><span class="text"></span><span class="tag open"><span class="begin">&lt;h5</span><span class="end">&gt;</span></span><span class="text">The Exclusivity of Jesus</span><span class="tag close">&lt;/h5&gt;</span><span class="text"></span></span></content></line>
<line id="94"><marker></marker><content><span class="context-markup xml"><span class="text"></span></span></content></line>
<line id="95"><marker></marker><content><span class="context-markup xml"><span class="text"></span><span class="tag open"><span class="begin">&lt;p</span><span class="end">&gt;</span></span><span class="text">In the days following Jesus' crucifixion and resurrection, the relatively small group of followers quickly increase. The miraculous signs performed through the Holy Spirit and the love they showed to one another drew a lot of attention not only from those who were genuinely interested in the new teaching that was promising eternal life but also from the priesthood and the Pharisees who had opposed Jesus in his lifetime. Now a cohesive and bold group Jesus' disciples posed a great threat to the old religion. For this reason, they denounced "The Way" as a sect apart from Judaism and the Roman authorities became suspicious of this community who were proclaiming a man other than Caesar as god and lord. Persecution soon followed and dialogue with the culture was very difficult if not impossible. Many believers held on to their confession of Jesus as the true Son of God and the only Lord at the cost of their lives. Later on during Constantine's reign when Christianity became the official religion of the Roman Empire there was very little need for theologians to engage with other faiths.</span><span class="tag close">&lt;/p&gt;</span><span class="text"></span></span></content></line>
<line id="96"><marker></marker><content><span class="context-markup xml"><span class="text"></span></span></content></line>
<line id="97"><marker></marker><content><span class="context-markup xml"><span class="text"></span><span class="tag open"><span class="begin">&lt;h5</span><span class="end">&gt;</span></span><span class="text">The Universal Church</span><span class="tag close">&lt;/h5&gt;</span><span class="text"></span></span></content></line>
<line id="98"><marker></marker><content><span class="context-markup xml"><span class="text"></span></span></content></line>
<line id="99"><marker></marker><content><span class="context-markup xml"><span class="text"></span><span class="tag open"><span class="begin">&lt;p</span><span class="end">&gt;</span></span><span class="text">The diversity of believers that were joining the Church coming from various religious backgrounds and the questions that they asked determined the pastors and the bishops of the time to look for an official/standard answer in the fourth and fifth centuries. Their task was even more quickened by the proposition of several interpretations of Jesus' story that were deviating from that of the apostles as it had been passed down through the mainstream gospels. Soon these interpretations (Arianism, Macedonianism, Nestorianism, Pelagianism) were repudiated as heresies and the creeds were formulated in order to unite the Christian groups around the world under a universal confession. The language that they employed was primarily derived from Greek philosophy and had very little to do with the language through which believers would understand their own spiritual experiences. A huge gap was introduced between theologians and the people who would go to church on a Sunday that continues through this day. Despite the efforts of pastors and preachers to apply the new expression of faith to the concrete situation of their local congregations sermons were often theoretical and failed to inspire the listeners in the pews.</span><span class="tag close">&lt;/p&gt;</span><span class="text"></span></span></content></line>
<line id="100"><marker></marker><content><span class="context-markup xml"><span class="text"></span></span></content></line>
<line id="101"><marker></marker><content><span class="context-markup xml"><span class="text"></span><span class="tag open"><span class="begin">&lt;h5</span><span class="end">&gt;</span></span><span class="text">Reflecting on what really happened</span><span class="tag close">&lt;/h5&gt;</span><span class="text"></span></span></content></line>
<line id="102"><marker></marker><content><span class="context-markup xml"><span class="text"></span></span></content></line>
<line id="103"><marker></marker><content><span class="context-markup xml"><span class="text"></span><span class="tag open"><span class="begin">&lt;p</span><span class="end">&gt;</span></span><span class="text">As time went by the original story of Jesus was partially contaminated. The fast speed at which Christianity spread across Europe was not without negative consequences. While the new faith became the de facto religion of most officials, the Greek myths survived among the vast majority of the population within the Empire. These were complemented by the miracle stories about the life of saints and martyrdoms. At the same time the new political power that Christian leaders enjoyed was a major factor to the increase of corruption among the clerics. By the time the practice of pilgrimages and indulgences was introduced, dissident groups were beginning to rise. They made a considerable effort to recover the original meaning of the Christian narrative. The focus was on the death of Christ and its implications. What was sin all about and how could we be saved? While invaluable theological reflections took place in Christendom, many aspects of salvation such as healing (physical and emotional), reconciliation of relationships (between rich and poor) were missed in the process. The understanding of atonement as expressed in the ransom, satisfaction, Christus Victor, and penal substitution theories dealt primarily with God, the right of Satan over sinners' lives, and the bondage of sin. Little consideration was given to the individual's responsibility to change his lifestyle and participate in the transformation of society. Jesus has accomplished everything for us. All we had to do was to accept the free gift of salvation.</span><span class="tag close">&lt;/p&gt;</span><span class="text"></span></span></content></line>
<line id="104"><marker></marker><content><span class="context-markup xml"><span class="text"></span></span></content></line>
<line id="105"><marker></marker><content><span class="context-markup xml"><span class="text"></span><span class="tag open"><span class="begin">&lt;h4</span><span class="end">&gt;</span></span><span class="text">Challenges posed by contemporary culture</span><span class="tag close">&lt;/h4&gt;</span><span class="text"></span></span></content></line>
<line id="106"><marker></marker><content><span class="context-markup xml"><span class="text"></span></span></content></line>
